Here's a typical approach:

**1. Define theme resource dictionaries**

Create separate XAML files for each theme (e.g., `Resources/Styles/LightTheme.xaml`, `DarkTheme.xaml`, `HighContrastTheme.xaml`):

```xml
<!-- LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="PrimaryText">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

**2. Consume theme resources with `DynamicResource`**

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryText}" Text="Hello" />
</ContentPage>
```

Using `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) ensures values update at runtime.

**3. Create a theme-switching helper**

```csharp
public static class ThemeManager
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(string theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove existing theme dictionary (always the last one added)
        mergedDicts.Clear();

        ResourceDictionary newTheme = theme switch
        {
            "Dark"         => new DarkTheme(),
            "HighContrast" => new HighContrastTheme(),
            _              => new LightTheme()
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(newTheme);

        // Persist choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", theme);
    }
}
```

**4. Apply on startup** (`App.xaml.cs`)

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", "Light");
    ThemeManager.ApplyTheme(saved);
}
```

**5. Settings page picker**

```csharp
void OnThemeSelected(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    var picker = (Picker)sender;
    ThemeManager.ApplyTheme(picker.SelectedItem.ToString()!);
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`DynamicResource`** is required for live switching — `StaticResource` only resolves once.
- Keep the same `x:Key` names across all three dictionaries so controls resolve correctly regardless of theme.
- Use `Preferences` (MAUI Essentials) for persistence so the choice survives app restarts.
- If you also want to respect the OS light/dark setting as a default, check `Application.Current.RequestedTheme` at startup and fall back accordingly.
